{{page-title "Documentation — Scrapes"}}
<div class="container mx-auto max-w-3xl py-6 px-4 space-y-6">

  <Panel::Card>
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">Scrapes</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      A Scrape is a raw captured snapshot of a job posting webpage. It's the input that becomes
      a Job Post. Career Caddy fetches the page, stores the HTML, and then parses it into
      structured fields (title, company, description, requirements). If you've ever lost a job
      listing because the company removed it before your interview, Scrapes are why that won't
      happen again.
    </p>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of the scrapes list" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Manual vs. Automated Scraping</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-1">Manual (in-app)</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
          Paste a job listing URL into the Scrape form. Career Caddy fetches the page and stores
          the raw content. Then click "Parse" to extract structured fields and create a Job Post.
          This works for any publicly accessible URL.
        </p>
        {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of the manual scrape form" /> --}}
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-1">Automated (AI pipeline)</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
          The AI pipeline watches your job alert emails (via notmuch), extracts URLs, and
          automatically scrapes and adds them to Career Caddy. This is configured in the
          <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">ai/</code> layer and requires local setup.
          See the root README for details.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">The Parse Step</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-3">
      After fetching a page, the raw HTML needs to be parsed into structured data. Click
      "Parse" on a Scrape record to extract:
    </p>
    <ul class="text-gray-600 text-sm list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
      <li>Job title</li>
      <li>Company name</li>
      <li>Full job description text</li>
      <li>Requirements / qualifications</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-3">
      Parsing creates a linked Job Post from the extracted data. Review and edit the Job Post
      fields before saving — automated parsing isn't perfect.
    </p>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of a scrape with the parse button and status showing Parsed" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Retry</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      If a scrape fails (network error, blocked by the site, or returns garbled content), use
      the "Retry" button to re-fetch the URL. Some job boards use JavaScript rendering that
      makes static scraping difficult — the browser-based scraping mode handles these cases
      better.
    </p>
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Example Scrape</h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded p-4 text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-2">
      <div><span class="font-semibold">URL:</span> <span class="text-blue-600">https://jobs.acme.example/sfullstack-123</span></div>
      <div><span class="font-semibold">Status:</span> <span class="bg-green-100 text-green-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full text-xs">Parsed</span></div>
      <div><span class="font-semibold">Scraped:</span> April 1, 2026</div>
      <div><span class="font-semibold">Linked Job Post:</span> Senior Full-Stack Engineer at Acme Corp</div>
    </div>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of this example scrape record in the show view" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

</div>
